<Collection><ShortName>GHRSST LEVEL 3P USA REMOTE SENSING SYSTEMS AMSRE SST</ShortName><VersionId>1</VersionId><InsertTime>2007-07-10T00:00:00.000Z</InsertTime><LastUpdate>2011-01-21T17:10:13.000Z</LastUpdate><LongName>GHRSST-PP L3P Global Sea Surface Temperature SSTsub-skin observations from the AQUA Advanced Scanning Microwave Radiometer - Earth Observing System (AMSR-E)</LongName><DataSetId>GHRSST Level 3P USA Remote Sensing Systems AMSRE SST:1</DataSetId><Description>The Advanced Microwave Scanning Radiometer (AMSR-E) was launched on May 4, 2002, aboard NASA's Aqua spacecraft. The National Space Development Agency of Japan (NASDA) provided AMSR-E to NASA as an indispensable part of Aqua's global hydrology mission. Over the oceans, AMSR-E is measuring a number of important geophysical parameters, including sea-surface temperature (SST), wind speed, atmospheric water vapor, cloud water, and rain rate. A key feature of AMSR-E is its capability to see through clouds, thereby providing an uninterrupted view of global SST and surface wind fields.</Description><Orderable>false</Orderable><Visible>true</Visible><RevisionDate>2011-06-08T08:31:45.513Z</RevisionDate><ProcessingCenter>Remote Sensing System</ProcessingCenter><ProcessingLevelId>3</ProcessingLevelId><ArchiveCenter>PO.DAAC</ArchiveCenter><DataFormat>NETCDF</DataFormat><SpatialKeywords><Keyword>Global</Keyword></SpatialKeywords><TemporalKeywords /><Temporal><RangeDateTime><BeginningDateTime>2002-06-01T12:06:00.000Z</BeginningDateTime></RangeDateTime></Temporal><Contacts><Contact><Role>Archiver</Role><OrganizationName>Physical Oceanography Distributed Active Archive Center, Jet Propulsion Laboratory, NASA</OrganizationName><OrganizationAddresses /><OrganizationPhones><Phone><Number>818-393-6710</Number><Type>Primary</Type></Phone></OrganizationPhones><OrganizationEmails><Email>edward.m.armstrong@jpl.nasa.gov</Email></OrganizationEmails><ContactPersons><ContactPerson><FirstName>Edward</FirstName><MiddleName>none</